{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"85b598a1-658d-4f88-b995-39b293e206c5","content":"## Collecting a CPU Trace on Windows (.NET 8)\n\n**Best tool: `dotnet-trace`** (lightweight, .NET-aware, no install beyond the global tool).\n\n### Quick steps\n\n```powershell\n# 1 – Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# 2 – Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3 – Collect a CPU-sampling trace (default ~1 ms sampling)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or convert to `.speedscope.json`:\n\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert <file>.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n### Alternatives worth knowing\n\n| Tool | When to prefer it |\n|---|---|\n| **PerfView** | Need OS-level ETW events, GC details, or kernel stacks alongside managed stacks |\n| **dotnet-counters** | Quick triage first — see if CPU is GC, JIT, or user code |\n| **Windows Performance Recorder (WPR)** | Deep kernel + user-mode analysis in WPA |\n\n### Pro tip — triage first\n\n```powershell\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\n\nWatch `% Time in GC` and `ThreadPool Queue Length` — if GC is high, you want a GC/allocation trace (`--profile gc-collect`) rather than a CPU one.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8b57b4e6-8ded-466e-ac8b-b5d306553d7c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question - no code changes or file operations needed.","outputTokens":434,"requestId":"CAA1:204F5C:1CF16FE:2012ABA:6A05252C"},"id":"37ef50e9-e972-4f1d-856b-dfb9b64c5574","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:28:25.466Z","parentId":"ad6771e0-564f-44cc-9885-d2817cf861ca"}
